    <section id="why">
        <div class="page-header">
            <h1><span class="blue-font">Odalisk</span> ?</h1>
        </div>
        <div class="page-body">
            <p>Odalisk stands for Open Data Live Score ChecKing !<br/>
			What does it mean? We crawl through a whole bunch of datasets, chew through the data we collect and calculate scores that represent the openness of each dataset. Then we agregate these results at the portal level, mix in some more data, and here we have our score! Our goal is to help promote the Opendata movement by providing an oversight on how the data is set free.</p>
            <div class="row">
                <div class="span4">
                    <h3>Why <span class="blue-font">Odalisk</span> ?</h3>
                    <p>The Opendata movement has been a reality for quite some time now, but recently we have witnessed a real rush : everyone wants to put their data out there. While the idea is great, the ways in which the data is liberated vary wildly. Some are very good at it, others not so much, and a lot inbetween. In order for the data to be usable, it needs to be liberated in ways that achieve a certain level of standardization. That's what we want to help achieve.</p>

                </div>
                <div class="span4">
                    <h3>Objectives</h3>
                    <p>
					<ol>
						<li>Come up with a list of robust, meaningful criterias to determine how open a dataset or portal is.</li>
						<li>Find ways to check automatically for these criterias. This allows us to scale to a vast number of datasets</li>
						<li>Analyse all of that data and display it in a sexy, easy to grasp way</li>
					</ol>
					</p>

                </div>
                <div class="span4">
                    <h3>Our workflow</h3>
                    <p>
					<ol>
					    <li>Find some portals that we are interested in checking for openness</li>
						<li>Find the urls for all the datasets</li>
						<li>Download all of these webpages</li>
						<li>Parse the HTML code and extract useful data</li>
						<li>Find the answer to our criterias from the data we extracted</li>
						<li>Agregate it in meaningful ways and display it</li>
					</ol>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

